SIMPLE: sinecure
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sinecure
<hw>Si`ne*cure</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>sine</ets>
without + <ets>cura</ets> care, LL., a cure. See <er>Cure</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>An ecclesiastical benefice without the care of
souls.</def> <rj><au>Ayliffe.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any office or position which requires or involves
little or no responsibility, labor, or active service.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A lucrative <qex>sinecure</qex> in the Excise.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sinecure</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sinecure
<hw>Si"ne*cure</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To put or place in a
sinecure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sinecurism</ent>⟦br⟧
